            . I am an officer. I got these things from a shop the prisoner had to repair; I found them in a cupboard on the Wednesday following - he was then in custody.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-180-person1502">
                  ARNOLD 
                  STEAD
               <interp inst="t18300527-180-person1502" type="surname" value="STEAD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-180-person1502" type="given" value="ARNOLD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-180-person1502" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I have known the prisoner upwards of five years, and employed him to fit up a counter and some shelves in a shop - he asked me to let him leave these things for a few days, and these books were among them.</p>
               <p>The prisoner put in a written Defence, stating that the prosecutor owed him wages amounting to 10l., and had lent him the tools in question.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-180-person1503">
                  THOMAS 
                  WILSON WELLS
               <interp inst="t18300527-180-person1503" type="surname" value="WILSON WELLS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-180-person1503" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18300527-180-person1503" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             re-examined. Q. Did you owe him wages? A. No, nor tell him what he has stated - I never gave him leave to pawn my tools; I have known him do it in several instances, and when I was at Edmonton I know he took a bed quilt, but he told me of it, and I said I would say no more about it - I was three weeks in the Fleet-prison, in September last; he did work for me then, but I owe him nothing - I have not employed him since January, but he lodged in my house; I did not see him from the Sunday till the Thursday, when I was standing in New-street, Covent-garden; he passed me - I got a Police-man, and took him afterwards, when I found where he lodged; we had a quarrel some time before, because he locked my premises, and I could not get in.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18300527-180-person1504">
                  THOMAS 
                  PERRING
               <interp inst="t18300527-180-person1504" type="surname" value="PERRING"></interp>
